Question Triff: Are feelings equal to thought?<br>
Is love equal to truth?<br>
Which is more important Triff? or are they equally important?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->What I stated before is that emotions (feelings) stem from what your values are. Your values are formed either by what you have thought out yourself, or—if you have <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> not</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> done that—based on whatever your subconscious has deemed is good or bad as you go through life (this would be closer to &quot;your feelings&quot; actually). This being so, what you (<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> truly</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->) think/believe will govern what you feel, and so I consider thought more important.<br>
<br>
Love is a strong happy feeling you get towards someone or something that follows your values (i.e. you value him/her/it a lot). It is not causeless, not a feeling that just magically appears out of nowhere. Trying to know and understand the truth is the only way you can logically form your own values.<br>
<br>
I don't consider love as such to be a virtue, but I do consider the <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> ability</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> to truly love as one. And I think that to truly/fully love something, you must first understand your values and work out all contradictions there may be in your thinking. I think that Reason is the most important tool of any human being.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> * * *</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Dunkk:<br>
The very miracle that is life, is proof positive that a higher power is at work in the universe.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->No, it is proof positive that there is life... that's about it. And if you think it is straight proof that there's a god, then what is the existence of a god proof of? The god's god? Et cetera.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Dunkk:<br>
...science can't explain why the nucleus doesn't fly apart, and long before anyone knew what a cell or a proton was Jesus had claimed the credit for it.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Three things...<br>
<br>
First: I think you are taking that quote and twisting its meaning to be a reference to nuclei (you think he was talking to people about atoms in the 1st century?). There is no evidence to support that—it's pretty similar to the people telling you to type in NYC in wingdings and heralding it as a link to terrorism.<br>
<br>
Second: Even supposing he did mean that, where is your proof that there was no one who had understood atomic science back then? There are any number of possibilities (from hidden civilizations to alien intervention) to lead to that; but even if none of those happened and somehow he still said it with that meaning in mind—it is not proof.<br>
<br>
Third: Where is your proof that there was a divine Jesus who ever said anything like that in the first place? All you have to cite for evidence is your Bible and some historical evidence that some man named Jesus probably did exist sometime around Year 0, around that relevent location.<br>
<br>
I don't see proof positive here.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> * * *</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Lukaria:<br>
...God exists outside science...<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->But science is the study of reality... you aren't saying God exists outside of reality, ..are you?<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Lukaria:<br>
