Brutas,  In the act of asking one has to assent to the idea they are talking to something real... to something that can hear the question. But, if Triff doesn't know there is a god (i.e., he has no reasonable justification to believe and there is in fact a god) then he can't sincerely ask god for knowledge. It would be like me, a non-believer in Santa Claus, popping a letter in the mail addressed to Santa in the North Pole. Why would I even consider it? I would have to have some reasonable justification for sitting down to write the letter from the start! Likewise, the act of asking god requires that I have justification to believe that my request will be heard. <b>In other words, in order to ask I must already believe.</b> <p>Lurikeen Mali'Kyre<BR>
